gher level of child mortality than before or after the war, caused by an upsurge of infectious diseases. Child health in Denmark, on the other hand, declined during the occupation years, and infectious diseases rose only marginally there. In spite of similar policies, hence, the outcome in terms of the biological standard of living was dissimilar. By closely investigating the impact of various policies on everyday life, and the amounts of goods available to different groups of consumers, this study identifies the causes of this remarkable divergence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aCost and standard of livingzDenmark. 0aCost and standard of livingzNetherlands. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zDenmark. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zNetherlands. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aKoetsenruijter, W., eeditor.1 aYing-Hui, Hsieh, eauthor.1 ade Jong, J., eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2002-2015z978311066278808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam Univ.Press  eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048521050zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048521050.jpg  a978-3-11-060651-5  Amsterdam Univ.Press  eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066278-8  AUP eBook Package Backlist 2002-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG